# üêû Bug report
Part of angular.json will look like the following
```js

"serve": {
                    "builder": "@angular-devkit/build-angular:dev-server",
                    "options": {
                       ...
                       "browserTarget": "project:build",
                    },
                    "configurations": {
                        
                        "conf": {
                            "browserTarget": "project:build,conf"
                        },
                    }}
```
Default ng serve uses the `browerTarget: project:build`.
`ng serve` will work; there is no problem there. 
If this browserTarget configuration is to be extended as `project:build,conf`, the following error is thrown when running `ng serve -c=conf`
>An unhandled exception occurred: Invalid target: {"project":"project","target":"build,conf"}

If we are to use the default value and override it with conf, we rather need to use

``` js
  "conf": {
                "browserTarget": "project:build:conf"
             },
```
Should not both be possibly accepted as this second way of writing makes it less obvious that the default config is being overriden ?

# üöÄ Feature request
Following this [PR](https://github.com/angular/angular-cli/pull/15819) it is now possible to extend build configuration.
Could it not possible to extends `serve` as well ? Additionnallly, `ng serve ` always searches for entries under ng-serve. Could it not be possible that if those entries are not present it uses values directly under `build` ?
### Description
 if we suppose that we have 2 build environment and 3 localize entries, we will need 6 entries under `serve` to test it locally.
```js
{
  "configurations": {
    "production": {
      "fileReplacements": [
        {
          "replace": "src/environments/environment.ts",
          "with": "src/environments/environment.prod.ts"
        }
      ]
    },
    "production2": {
      "fileReplacements": [
        {
          "replace": "src/environments/environment.ts",
          "with": "src/environments/environment.prod2.ts"
        }
      ]
    },
    "li18n1": {},
    "li18n2": {},
    "li18n3": {}
  }
}
```
If we are to use all these configs values under serve, we will need 6 entries. I wonder if it cannot be possible to run ng serve -c="i18n1, production1" and to directly use both configs
